      </div>
      <p class="note"><strong>Note:</strong> Not all platforms support all Unicode characters. Most modern platforms work great, but some characters might not display on older systems.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="explanation card">
      <h2>How It Works</h2>
      <p>These aren't actually "fonts" — they're <strong>Unicode characters</strong> from different character blocks. The Unicode standard defines over 149,000 characters including Mathematical Alphanumeric Symbols, Enclosed Alphanumerics, and many more decorative character sets.</p>
      
      <p>When you type "A", this generator swaps it for similar-looking characters like <strong>𝔸</strong> (Double-Struck A), <strong>𝒜</strong> (Script A), or <strong>🅐</strong> (Negative Squared A). Since these are real characters with their own Unicode code points, they work everywhere without installing any fonts.</p>

      <p>That's why fancy text works on Instagram, Discord, Twitter, and virtually any modern platform — you're not changing fonts, you're typing completely different characters that happen to look like styled versions of regular letters.</p>

      <div class="unicode-blocks">
        <h3>Unicode Character Blocks Used</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Mathematical Alphanumeric Symbols</strong> (U+1D400–1D7FF) — Bold, italic, script, fraktur, double-struck</li>
          <li><strong>Enclosed Alphanumerics</strong> (U+2460–24FF) — Circled letters and numbers</li>
          <li><strong>Enclosed Alphanumeric Supplement</strong> (U+1F100–1F1FF) — Squared letters</li>
          <li><strong>Combining Diacritical Marks</strong> (U+0300–036F) — Zalgo and strikethrough effects</li>
          <li><strong>Halfwidth and Fullwidth Forms</strong> (U+FF00–FFEF) — Wide/vaporwave text</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq card">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How do fancy text generators work?</h3>
        <p>Fancy text generators replace standard Latin letters with visually similar Unicode characters from different blocks like Mathematical Alphanumeric Symbols. These are real characters, not fonts, so they work everywhere without installing anything.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Will fancy text work on Instagram?</h3>
        <p>Yes! Since these are Unicode characters, they work on Instagram, Twitter/X, Discord, TikTok, Facebook, YouTube and virtually any platform that supports Unicode text.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What is Zalgo text?</h3>
        <p>Zalgo text uses combining diacritical marks (U+0300-036F) to create a corrupted, glitchy appearance. The marks stack above and below letters, creating the signature "cursed" look popular in memes and horror aesthetics.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Why don't some characters show up?</h3>
        <p>Some platforms or devices may not support all Unicode blocks. Most modern platforms support the common fancy text styles, but very new or obscure Unicode characters might not render on older systems.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Is fancy text the same as a font?</h3>
        <p>No. Fonts change how characters are displayed, while fancy text uses different Unicode characters entirely. Fancy text works everywhere because you're typing actual different characters, not changing the font style.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

